column7: SAMPLE SENTENCE
She is an ``indefatigable` hiker and can walk all day.
Davey is the ``indisputable` star of the basketball team.

column5: The ability to have an impact of something
column7: My 11-year old nephew has been a positive ``influence` on his younger brother.
The cleaning spray ``inhibits` the growth of bacteria.

column4: {'Initialed':'(verb)','Initialing':'(verb)','Initials':'(noun) - the first letters of a name or a word'}
column5: The first.\nExisting or occurring at the beginning
column7: Obama was the ``initial` black president of the US.

column5: An investigation to determine the truth
column7: Congress launched an ``inquiry` after President Clinton was accused of having relations with Monika Lewinski.
You can't quit the team since you are an ``integral` part of the unit.
When making a cake, you need to fully ``integrate` the wet and dry ingredients.

column5: To explain the meaning of something
column7: I need you to ``interpret` the Chinese menu for Joe.

column5: To come between people, or an event and change what is happening
column7: When the toddlers couldn't share their toys, their mothers had to ``intervene`.
The ``intrepid` mountain climber reached the top of Mt.Everest.
The pattern on this blanket is so ``intricate`.
We found the stranger's questions too personal and very ``invasive`.
The police are going to ``investigate` the crime scene.
Even though my grandfather seems ``irascible`, he's actually very loving.

column4: {'Irony':'(noun) - of or like iron - an irony gray color'}
column5: The use of words to give a meaning opposite to their literal meaning
column7: 'I love linear algebra,' he said with ``irony`.
Not sure which direction to go in, he stood ``irresolute`.

column5: Words specific to a certain job or group
column7: To be a successful engineer, you'll need to learn a lot of technical ``jargon`.

My Chinese friend has a great ``knack` for solving technical problems.
Building a house requires a lot of ``labor`.
I stayed with the front group of runners for the first few miles, but after that I began to ``lag` behind.
The cartoonist ``lampooned` President Trump's tweet. (or his hair, speech, behavior, intelligence, etc)

column5: To become weak; to be neglected
column7: During spring break, my plants ``languished` since I was traveling the world and couldn't water them.

column5: A talk given to an audience
column7: TED TALKS are interesting, informative ``lectures`.

It's ``ludicrous` to say 'President' before the word Trump.

column5: To continue at the same level
column7: She has ``maintained` the same weight since high school.
Writing is a ``major` skill for English proficiency.

column5: To influence, especially in an unfair way
column7: Russia tried to ``manipulate` the results of the American election.

column5: To increase to the greatest possible size
column7: Your goal, along with learning, is to ``maximize` your GPA.

column5: To find the size and dimensions of something
column7: By ``measuring` his gut, we can conclude that he drinks too much beer.
The meals at the cafeteria are ``mediocre`.
My mom will ``mend` the hole in my pants.
The Japanese ``method` of communicating is indirect.

column5: To move from one place to another
column7: Many Chinese laborers ``migrate` to Shenzhen.

column5: The smallest of lowest amount possible
column7: You need to get a ``minimum` of 60% to pass English.
